    <a title="Luís" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s"><img alt="Luís" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1636480820p2/117399210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3908555645?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luís" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luís" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s">Luís</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789896230401" href="/book/show/4029720-gente-independente">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=e-5-favourites">e-5-favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-classics">g-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-historical-fiction">g-historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=iceland">iceland</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3908555645" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1260299196231630107">Iceland. Its landscapes, its northern lights, its volcanoes with unpronounceable names. We cannot say that it has an insane number of writers (or inhabitants, it must be said). Halldór Laxness, 1955 Nobel Prize for Literature, is generally considered the greatest. A funny character who has had his bump quite a bit and keen to help people discover his country.<br/>Nowadays, we have Iceland&apos;s image as a small, prosperous, democratic paradise, ideal for tourism. We do not know or forget that it was one </span>
  <span id="freeText1260299196231630107" style="display:none">Iceland. Its landscapes, its northern lights, its volcanoes with unpronounceable names. We cannot say that it has an insane number of writers (or inhabitants, it must be said). Halldór Laxness, 1955 Nobel Prize for Literature, is generally considered the greatest. A funny character who has had his bump quite a bit and keen to help people discover his country.<br />Nowadays, we have Iceland's image as a small, prosperous, democratic paradise, ideal for tourism. We do not know or forget that it was one of the worst pits in the world not so long ago.<br />In the 1900s, a farmer, Bjartur, decided to set up on his own. With his flock of sheep and his young wife, he goes to live in the mountains, in the depths of a desolate moor windswept. There is plenty of pasture and no human presence for miles. He wants to live governed by his will alone and by nature, under the guidance of no one.<br />Like most of the Iceland peasants, they live in a mud hut half-buried and full of smoke, sleep on low slopes, and eat scraps of fish. Potatoes are a dish for the rich. The rain falls almost continuously. That's a precarious existence that requires a daily struggle, in almost total solitude. The novel takes place over two or three decades. Around Bjartur, people live, die or go in search of a better destiny. It remains the pivot of the story. Leading his life like a boat amid a storm, he never gets discouraged; he never gives up. He continues on his way, tracing straight ahead as an independent man.<br />The degree of misery that Halldór Laxness shows us would make the Thenardiers look like a wealthy bourgeois. It is a world of total hardness, far from the postcard image we have today. That's to think about if you have the chance to travel there.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1260299196231630107" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


